From 051b21c1e38eb9d9f4b6ab3acaa8e41af568c944 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: souliane <21343492+souliane@users.noreply.github.com>
Date: Mon, 22 Jun 2026 15:36:16 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 3/3] fix(loop): serialize slack_mentions and
 slack_review_intent scanners to enforce ordering invariant
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

The slack_review_intent scanner reads an in-memory reactions queue that
slack_mentions populates. The scan phase fans scanners across a thread pool,
so list order alone cannot guarantee execution order — slack_review_intent
could start before slack_mentions completes, observing an empty queue.

Introduce serial_scanner_chains() to group dependent scanner pairs into single
execution units that run serially on one worker. The pool still fans out
independent scanners in parallel, preserving concurrency where safe.

Dependencies are declared explicitly in _SCANNER_DEPENDENCIES keyed on scanner
names, making the constraint stable regardless of job construction order or
class import order. A dependent scanner without its depended-upon scanner in
a given tick still executes (just without the ordering guarantee).

Test plan:
- test_slack_mentions_before_review_intent_in_messaging_jobs: Verify list order
- test_scanner_ordering_with_random_iterations: Randomized list order test
- test_review_intent_observes_drained_queue: Verify execution order (main flake fix)

Open questions & assumptions:

- Dependent scanners without their depended-upon scanner in a tick fall back to
  independent execution. This is safe: slack_review_intent will see an empty
  queue, which is a valid (if suboptimal) state.

- Only explicitly declared dependencies are serialized. Other scanners still
  fan out across the pool. With one dependency pair and both typically present,
  performance impact is negligible.

